07959nam a22010695i 9781788923071DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20192019enk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817889230717 a10.21832/97817889230712doi  a(DE-B1597)527564  a(OCoLC)1100436501  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aenkcGB-BST 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a306.44/922300aAWorld of Indigenous Languages :bPolitics, Pedagogies and Prospects for Language Reclamation /ced. by Teresa L. McCarty, Sheilah E. Nicholas, Gillian Wigglesworth. 1aBristol ;aBlue Ridge Summit : bMultilingual Matters, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLinguistic Diversity and Language Rights00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tContributors -- tAcknowledgements -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. A World of Indigenous Languages – Resurgence, Reclamation, Revitalization and Resilience -- tPart 1: Policies and Politics in Indigenous Language Reclamation -- t1. Configuring Language(s) and Speakers: The History and Politics of an Aboriginal Ethnolinguistic Identity in the Yukon, Canada -- t2. Language Policy in Post-Apartheid South Africa – An Evaluation -- tPart 2: Pedagogies and Processes in Indigenous Language Reclamation -- t3. The Impact of ‘Culturalcy’ in Ngā Kura ā Iwi Tribal Schools in Aotearoa/NZ: Mō Tātou, Mā Tātou, E Ai Ki a Tātou – For Us, By Us, Our Way -- t4. Media and Technology: Revitalizing Latin American Indigenous Languages in Cyberspace -- t5. Language Vitality In and Out of School in a Remote Indigenous Australian Context -- t6. Task-Based Language Learning for Ojibwe: A Case Study of Two Intermediate Adult Language Learners -- t7. Strengthening Indigenous Languages through Language Technology: The Case of Aanaar Saami in Finland -- tPart 3: Prospects and Possibilities for Indigenous Language Reclamation -- t8. Without the Language, How Hopi Are You?: Hopi Cultural and Linguistic Identity Construction in Contemporary Linguistic Ecologies -- t9. Transformation from the Bottom Up: Ideological Analysis with Indigenous Youth and Language Policy Justice in Nepal -- t10. Language Key Holders for Mexicano: The Case of an Intergenerational Community in Coatepec de los Costales, Mexico -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSpanning Indigenous settings in Africa, the Americas, Aotearoa/New Zealand, Australia, Central Asia and the Nordic countries, this book examines the multifaceted language reclamation work underway by Indigenous peoples throughout the world. Exploring political, historical, ideological, and pedagogical issues, the book foregrounds the decolonizing aims of contemporary Indigenous language movements inside and outside of schools. Many authors explore language reclamation in their own communities. Together, the authors call for expanded discourses on language planning and policy that embrace Indigenous ways of knowing and forefront grassroots language reclamation efforts as a force for Indigenous sovereignty, social justice, and self-determination. This volume will be of interest to scholars, educators and students in applied linguistics, Ethnic/Indigenous Studies, education, second language acquisition, and comparative-international education, and to a broader audience of language educators, revitalizers and policymakers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLanguage maintenance. 0aLanguage policy. 0aLanguage revival. 0aLinguistic minorities. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aIndigenous languages.  alanguage endangerment.  alanguage planning and policy.  alanguage reclamation.  alanguage revitalization.1 aBird, Pem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc